04664nam a22007095i 9781400821532DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19941994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984665857  a97814008215327 a10.1515/97814008215322doi  a(DE-B1597)446144  a(OCoLC)979685148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD9685.U6T219 1994 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a353.0082/3/097681 aHargrove, Erwin C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrisoners of Myth :bThe Leadership of the Tennessee Valley Authority, 1933-1990 /cErwin C. Hargrove.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in American Politics: Historical, International, and Comparative Perspectives ;v3900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER 1. History and Theory -- tPART I: The Founding Generation -- tCHAPTER 2. Visions of an Institution -- tCHAPTER 3. Lilienthal’s TVA: The Politics of Leadership -- tCHAPTER 4. The Development of TVA Organizational Culture -- tCHAPTER 5. The Organization in Action -- tEPILOGUE: PART I The Past as Prologue -- tPART II: Prisoners of Myth -- tCHAPTER 6. Consolidating Leadership: Clapp and Vogel -- tCHAPTER 7. Rise and Fall of the Dynamo -- tCHAPTER 8. The Politics of Organizational Renewal -- tCHAPTER 9. Denouement -- tEPILOGUE: PART II New Departures -- tCHAPTER 10. Reflections -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrisoners of Myth is the first comprehensive history of the Tennessee Valley Authority from its creation to the present day. It is also a telling case study of organizational evolution and decline. Building on Philip Selznick's classic work TVA and the Grass Roots (1949), a seminal text in the theoretical study of bureaucracy, Erwin Hargrove analyzes the organizational culture of the TVA by looking at the actions of its leaders over six decades--from the heroic years of the New Deal and World War II through the postwar period of consolidation and growth to the time of troubles from 1970 onward, when the TVA ran afoul of environmental legislation, built a massive nuclear power program that it could not control, and sought new missions for which there were no constituencies.The founding myth of multipurpose regional development was inappropriately pursued in the 1970s and '80s by leaders who became "prisoners of myth" in their attempt to keep the TVA heroic. A decentralized organization, which had worked well at the grass roots, was difficult to redirect as the nuclear genii spun out of control. TVA autonomy from Washington, once a virtue, obscured political accountability. This study develops an important new theory about institutional performance in the face of historical change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectric utilitieszTennessee River ValleyxManagementxHistory. 0aGovernment corporationszUnited StatesxManagementxHistory. 0aLeadership. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082153240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400821532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400821532.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK